Source: Zwire, EFE (via COMTEX), Tue 16 Jul 2002 [edited]
<http://www.zwire.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=4762676&BRD=1713&PAG=740&dept_id=226965&rfi=6>

Mexico: Public Health Alert Declared in Southern Border States of Mexico
------------------------------------------------------------------------
CANCUN: Officials in Mexico's southern border states have declared a
public health alert in the region following an outbreak of dengue
fever in Central America. The alert covers Quintana Roo, Chiapas, and
Campeche, where some 231 cases of the disease have been reported this
year, including 30 of the potentially deadly dengue hemorrhagic fever.
The outbreak has most affected Quintana Roo (where 157 cases have
been reported, including 21 dengue hemorrhagic fever cases) and
Chiapas, with 56 reported cases, Quintana Roo state Health Secretary
Dagoberto Garcia said. Garcia said 18 dengue cases, including 3 cases
of dengue hemorrhagic fever, have been reported in the Caribbean
resort city of Cancun. One of the country's most popular tourist
destinations, Cancun received 1.5 million visitors in the first half
of 2002.
Garcia said another 150 part-time health workers have been hired for
the remainder of 2002 to bolster the fight against infectious
diseases. According to Cancun health official Arturo Toledo, the
measure would also serve to contain diseases like malaria, cholera,
measles, and whooping cough, which he said had increased with the
influx of illegal immigrants from Central America.
